<HEADLINE> SDP Leader Blasts Dispatch of Evacuation Planes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Japan's Social Democratic Party
leader Takako Doi today blasted the government for using military
planes for possible airlift of Japanese nationals from Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
Ordered by Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto, three C-130 cargo
planes of the Air Self-Defense Forces have arrived in Thailand and
will stand by there to carry out an evacuation mission if needed.
</P>
<P>
Doi challenged the legality of the government decision, said a
Kyodo news agency report.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the "preparatory actions" that the government has
claimed as grounds for the dispatching, Doi said: "There is
nothing written about preparatory actions in the Self-Defense Law."
</P>
<P>
When the law was revised in 1994, she said, there was a "big
discussion" on the need to prevent the evacuation of Japanese from
leading to the dispatch of military forces overseas.
</P>
<P>
Government officials, however, argued that the deployment of
Japan's military planes for evacuations abroad became possible
under the 1994 revision of the Self-Defense Law.
</P>
<P>
Doi expressed displeasure with Hashimoto, who she said gave no
advance notice on the evacuation mission, to her party, a
coalition partner of Hashimoto's Liberal Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
"My party has not been informed of the move and no discussions
have been made on the matter," Kyodo quoted Doi as saying.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia, where hundreds of Japanese are staying, was on the
verge of a civil war after Second Prime Minister Hun Sen deposed
First Prime Minister Prince Norodom Ranariddh by force. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
