<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nine Injured in Renewed Violence in Hebron </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 12 (Xinhua) -- At least nine Palestinian
youths were injured today by Israeli soldiers in renewed clashes
in the flashpoint West Bank city of Hebron.
</P>
<P>
Reports from Hebron said that masked Palestinian youths
attacked with rocks and firebombs the Israeli troops stationed
inside an Arab school, where a torn copy of Islam's holy Koran
was found early this week.
</P>
<P>
Palestinians held the Israeli soldiers responsible for tearing
the Koran and responded with more violence. This incident added
fuel to the already tense situation sparked by the offensive
leaflets depicting Islamic prophet Mohammed as a pig, pasted by a
Jewish woman from Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Israeli soldiers returned rubber bullets and tear gas, injuring
at least nine Palestinian protesters. Jewish settlers also joined
in the clashes, throwing back rocks from roof-tops.
</P>
<P>
A firebomb was thrown at Israeli soldiers Friday night, but no
one was injured. This morning, Israeli soldiers dismantled a
home-made pipe bomb planted near the division line between the
Arab and Jewish quarters.
</P>
<P>
After redeploying troops from 80 percent of Hebron in
accordance with an agreement signed in January, Israel retains
control over the other 20 percent where some 450 Jewish settlers
are living.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Palestinian peace talks have been frozen since
March when Israel began building the controversial Har Homa
settlement in East Jerusalem. The Palestinian National Authority
(PA) is demanding a halt to the settlement activities before the
peace process can be resumed.
</P>
<P>
Despite the continued clashes in Hebron, there was a positive
sign for reconciliation between Israel and the PNA: Israel
announced today that the two sides would resume talks Sunday to
discuss cooperation in the construction of a Palestinian airport
in Dahaniya, Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
The announcement came after Israeli and Palestinian officials
toured the building site on Friday. Israel is insisting on its
right to share the security control over the airport for fears
that weapons might be smuggled in to threaten its security.
</P>
<P>
If the disputes over the airport can be resolved and safe
passages for Palestinians to travel between West Bank and Gaza
Strip opened, observers here believe, it will pave the way for
resuming the deadlocked Israeli-Palestinian peace negotiations.
</P>
</TEXT>
