<HEADLINE> Report: Drug Use Prevalent among D.C. Prisoners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Nine percent of Washington D.C.
Department of Corrections prisoners tested positive for illegal
drugs during random checks over the last six months.
</P>
<P>
The percentage was almost four times the most recent national
average for state prison systems, The Washington Post reported in
its Saturday edition.
</P>
<P>
Between December through May, D.C. officials checked 5,685
prisoners for illicit drugs, and 512 inmates tested positive,
according to the Post.
</P>
<P>
Tests found the most common drug was marijuana, followed by
cocaine.
</P>
<P>
Corrections Director Margaret A. Moore said that illegal drugs
are being smuggled into the prisons by staff members, visitors and
sometimes through the mail.
</P>
<P>
Prisoner access to illegal drug has been a long-running problem
for District correctional officials, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
