<DOCNO> XIE19970713.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-12 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mediterranean Forum Raps Israeli Settlement Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALGIERS, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The 11-member Mediterranean Forum
today condemned Israel's policy of settlement in the occupied
Palestinian territories.
</P>
<P>
This came in a final statement issued when foreign ministers of
the forum's member countries wounded up a two-day conference here
today.
</P>
<P>
The ministers attending the fifth meeting of the forum
emphasized their opposition to the unilateral measures taken by
Israel, especially those concerning Jewish settlement in the
occupied Palestinian territories including Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
They pointed out that these measures are an insurmountable
obstacle to the Middle East peace process and expressed their
grave concern over the prevalent situation in the region.
</P>
<P>
They emphasized that the establishment of a fair, comprehensive
and lasting peace in the region should be based on relevant UN
Security Council resolutions, on respect for the land-for-peace
principle and the right of the Palestinian people to
self-determination.
</P>
<P>
They reaffirmed commitment and adherence to the peace process
in the light of the foundations laid down for it at the Madrid
conference, as well as their wish to push forward the peace
process in accordance with the agreements signed at the Oslo and
Washington conferences.
</P>
<P>
They also vowed to fight terrorism with all its forms, and
pledged to cooperate in the field of security.
</P>
<P>
The forum, established in 1994 as an informal gathering to
advance cooperation and partnership among nations on both sides of
the Mediterranean, consists of Tunisia, Morocco, Egypt, Italy,
Spain, Portugal, France, Turkey Greece, Malta and Algeria.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
