<HEADLINE> NSC to Send Mission to Aideed Over Reconciliation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Ali Mahdi Mohammed, current
chairman of the National Salvation Council (NSC) of Somalia,
today said his organization is soon to send a mission to Hussien
Aideed over reconciliation process.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to local journalists here, Ali Mahdi said the plan to
send the mission came after a NSC meeting held Friday on the
strategy and packages of the reconciliation process.
</P>
<P>
Ali Mahdi said the mission will meet Aideed at any venue he
(Aideed) suggests, adding that "we will not get tired of
contacting Aideed."
</P>
<P>
Asked what would NSC do if Aideed refuses to meet the council,
he said NSC would continue its efforts to bring "everybody on
board".
</P>
<P>
"But Somalia will not be hostage for anybody any more. Enough
is enough," he added.
</P>
<P>
At its second ordinary session held recently, the NSC decided
to hold the national reconciliation conference in Bossaso,
Somalia in November this year.
</P>
<P>
Ali Mahdi said he expects the establishment of a national
transitional government at the reconciliation conference due to
be held in Bossaso.
</P>
<P>
He said, "we expect that the international community would
help us politically, economically and morally in building up
Somalia again," adding that some members of the Arab League such
as Kuwait and Quatar have already expressed their readiness to
finance some of the expenses of the Bossaso conference.
</P>
<P>
The 26 faction NSC was established in January this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
