<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda, Djibouti Pledge to Tighten Bilateral Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Uganda and Djibouti issued a
joint communique here today, pledging to consolidate the existing
relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan President Y. Museveni and his Djibouti counterpart
Hassan Gouled Aptidon said in the communique that the existence
of air and sea links and future development of a road network
under the IGAD (Inter-Government Authority on Development)
infrastructure program, would improve trade and tourism between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
They also encouraged private sector entrepreneurs to
participate in commercial activities through their chambers of
commerce.
</P>
<P>
At the international level, they expressed concern over the
Middle East peace process and called for resumption of the
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a joint press conference here today, they
reiterated their full support for IGAD and their total confidence
in its value for the region.
</P>
<P>
They said that IGAD has an important role to play in
development in the region, and can also play a useful role as a
peaceful forum for solving problems.
</P>
<P>
Asked to comment on the process of reducing government
expenditure through demobilization in the army and reduction in
the civil service in Djibouti, Aptidon explained that after
resolving a four-year internal conflict in his country, the
government decided to reduce the size of the army.
</P>
<P>
He said his government has approached several international
bodies and friendly countries for support and has already
received pledges for support for the program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
