<HEADLINE> Sarajevo Airport Reopens After Temporary Closure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The Sarajevo Airport reopened on
Saturday after it was closed overnight following an alarm of
possible retaliation by Serbs in the wake of NATO's arresting of
war crime indictees, local press reports said.
</P>
<P>
According to the Sarajevan news agency ONASA, the airport was
reopened after the NATO-led Stablization Force deemed the closure
as unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
SFOR spokesman told ONASA that the situation both on the ground
and in the air in Bosnia is stable.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, NATO troops launched the first operation since
deployment to catch persons indicted for war crimes by an
international court in the Hague.
</P>
<P>
In the operation code-named "Tango", one Serb indictee was
killed when he tried to resist the arrest and a second Serb was
captured alive and transferred to the Hague afterwards. 
</P>
</TEXT>
