<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudan Pledges Perpetual Support to Kuwait </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Sudan said it will give
perpetual support to Kuwait and try its utmost to secure the quick
release of Kuwaiti Prisoners of War still being detained in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Sudan State Minister at the Foreign Affairs Mostapha Osman Ismail
said in an exclusive interview with official Kuwait News Agency
before concluding his week-long visit to Kuwait that Sudan "wants
to restore brotherly and normal ties" with Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Ismail arrived in Kuwait last Tuesday and this is the first
visit by a Sudanese government official since the ties between
the two Arab countries became strained due to Khartoum's support
of Iraq during the Gulf crisis in 1990-91.
</P>
<P>
The state minister said, "we took the opportunity to visit
our brothers in Kuwait to underscore that our policy will be
based firmly and strongly on perpetual support for Kuwait and
its causes."
</P>
<P>
He also said, "we will do whatever possible to secure the
release of all the prisoners still held by the Iraqi regime."
</P>
<P>
Kuwait insists that more than 600 Kuwaitis were still jailed in
Iraq and used every forum and opportunity to call on the
international community to press Iraq to give them freedom. Iraq
so far has given files of more than 100 Kuwaitis who were caught
in the period of Iraqi occupation and being detained in Baghdad,
but denied Kuwaiti allegations.
</P>
<P>
During his stay here, Ismail was received by Kuwaiti Amir
Sheikh Jaber Al-Ahmad Al-Sabah to whom he delivered a letter from
Sudanese President Omar Al-Bashir. The contents of the letter was
not revealed.
</P>
<P>
Diplomats here say the message is the first contact on the
level of the state leadership between the two countries since the
Gulf war and heralded a possible start of a slow reconciliation
process.
</P>
<P>
Ismail also held talks with Kuwaiti acting Prime Minister and
Foreign Minister Sheikh Sabah Al-Ahmad and described his meeting
was "successful and a step on the road towards the normalization
of relations between the two countries."
</P>
<P>
During his stay here, an agreement between Kuwait and Sudan
was made to start exchanging visits soon of non-political
delegations as a first step towards restoration of full ties.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait currently represented in Sudan by a Charge D'Affaires
while the Sudanese Embassy in Kuwait has been closed for more
than six years.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait accelerated the process of reconciling relations with
Arab countries including Sudan, Yemen, Jordan and the
Palestinians which supported Iraq during the Gulf War in 1991
that liberated the small oil-rich Gulf state from Iraqi
occupation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
