<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Proposes Training Program for Border Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 12 (Xinhua) -- A European Union (EU) official
Friday proposed an exchange and training program for officials
working with border control, immigration and asylum.
</P>
<P>
Anita Gradin, EU commissioner for justice and home affairs,
said, "To create a secure Europe with free movement for people the
member states have to cooperate against organized crime and
trafficking in human beings."
</P>
<P>
The program, called Odysseus, is aimed at training, exchange
and cooperation in the field of asylum, immigration, the crossing
of external borders and identification of false documents.
</P>
<P>
"We have to make sure that customs, police and judicial
authorities in all member states work together and understand each
other," Gradin emphasized.
</P>
<P>
The training will reportedly focus on instructors and
specialists especially decision makers and those in charge of
training.
</P>
<P>
There will be an exchange program for officials between
national administrative departments. The Odysseus also comprises
production of teaching material and circulation of information.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission will manage and monitor the program.
</P>
</TEXT>
