<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Irish PM Haughey to Testify at Tribunal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Former Irish Prime Minister Charles
Haughey is expected to testify later next week at a
payments-to-politicians tribunal investigating the case of Haughey
receiving a large sum of cash from an Irish tycoon.
</P>
<P>
Dennis McCullough, counsel for the tribunal, told the tribunal
in April that Haughey received 1.3 million Irish pounds (about 2
million U.S. dollars) from businessman Ben Dunne between 1987 and
1991.
</P>
<P>
Haughey, who had been Irish prime minister between 1979 and
1992, last week issued a statement through his legal team,
admitting for the first time that he was the recipient of the cash
and he also admitted misleading his lawyers, said reports from
Dublin.
</P>
<P>
Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern, who came to power after
winning a June 6 general election, is now facing increasing
opposition pressure to set up another tribunal to investigate
Haughey's case alone.
</P>
<P>
Ahern made it clear last week that the current tribunal would
have to run its course, but said he was keeping an "open mind"
about any new investigation into one of the most powerful
political figures in Irish politics since self-rule seven decades
ago.
</P>
<P>
Irish businessman Dunne had earlier admitted that he gave
Haughey the money in the form of three bank drafts of about 70,000
pounds (about 112,000 dollars), but he stressed that he never
expected "any favor or benefit" from the former prime minister.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
