<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, July 13 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON -- British policemen in Londonderry and north Belfast,
capital of Northern Ireland, were attacked with petrol bombs on
Saturday night after the main day of the Orange Order's marching
calendar passed without any major incidents.
</P>
<P>
Gangs using catapults armed with ball-bearings were also
involved in the attacks and Royal Ulster Constabulary (RUC)
officers responded by firing plastic bullets and making some
arrests, according to BBC television reports.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Israeli military authorities have decided to
tighten the screws against Palestinian resistance, the state-run
Israel Radio reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Israel Defense Forces (IDF) is preparing for a possible
escalation of violence in the Palestinian territories and,
particularly, further deterioration of situation in the West Bank
city of Hebron.
</P>
<P>
The move came after weeks of violent demonstrations and
protests in the West Bank and Gaza Strip resulted from Jewish
settlement expansion. An anti-Islamic poster depicting Prophet
Muhammad as a pig set off a wave of violent clashes between
Palestinians and Israeli soldiers in Hebron.
</P>
<P>
DHAKA -- The flash flood that hit nearly one-third of
Bangladesh has deteriorated further and the government called out
the armed forces to undertake emergency rescue and relief
operations in the affected areas.
</P>
<P>
The death toll in the sudden flood, caused by incessant
downpours for the last five days and on-rush of hilly water, has
risen to 57 as reports of fresh deaths are still reaching Dhaka
from the flood-hit areas.
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- Bosnian Serb President Biljana Plavsic Saturday
held a closed-door meeting with Momcilo Krajisnik, the Serb member
of Bosnia's three-member presidency, in her power base, Banja
Luka, said a report of the official Tanjug news agency.
</P>
<P>
This was the first meeting between the two Bosnian Serb
leaders, but they did not issue any formal statement after the
two-hour meeting.
</P>
<P>
Krajisnik only briefed the reporters that they were making some
progress during the talk that would continue tomorrow while
Plavsic remained silent.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was held when Plavsic was battling Bosnian Serb
hard-liners who see her as too moderate. She has been the only
senior Serb official to advocate closer compliance with the Dayton
accords and has accused the hard-line leadership of corruption.
</P>
</TEXT>
