<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Government Asks To Implement Open-ended Grain Purchase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Vice-premier Zhu Rongji, speaking
to a three-day meeting on grain purchase and sales Friday, urged
government offices nationwide to be strict in implementing the
state grain purchase policy that says local governments should buy
grain at protective prices from growers in an "open-ended" way.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was held July 9-11 and was attended by heads of
ministries and senior agricultural officials from all provinces,
municipalities and autonomous regions.
</P>
<P>
Zhu, who is also a member of the Standing Committee of the
Political Bureau of the Central Committee of the Communist Party
of China, said, "The policy is an important decision of the
Central Committee of the Communist Party of China and the State
Council for favorable agricultural development and the sustained,
speedy and sound development of the overall national economy."
</P>
<P>
The policy says that the state grain system must purchase grain
at subsidized prices and that state buyers can not reject, stop,
or limit grain purchase, or pay farmers with IOUs.
</P>
<P>
It also says that financial institutions should ensure
sufficient funds for this, and prohibits the use of this capital
for other purposes.
</P>
<P>
Vice-premier Li Lanqing, a member of Political Bureau of the
CPC Central Committee, spoke at the opening session of the
meeting, which was presided over by Luo Gan, state councillor and
secretary-general of the State Council.
</P>
<P>
China is expected to harvest 118 billion kg of grain this
summer, a 3.5 percent increase, or four billion kg, more than in
1996, an all-time high, according to the Ministry of
Agriculture. This will also be the third consecutive year that
China has had a good summer harvest.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970713.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia, U.S. Agree to Accelerate Modification of CFE Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister Evgeny
Primakov said today that Russia and the United States have agreed
to speed up the modification of the Treaty of Conventional Forces
in Europe (CFE).
</P>
<P>
After holding three hours of talks with visiting U.S. Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright in St.Petersburg, Primakov told
reporters that both countries were interested in updating the CFE
Treaty and "agreed to hold further talks before the end of July."
</P>
<P>
Russia and the U.S. cannot impose their decisions on other
signatories to the CFE Treaty, Primakov said.
</P>
<P>
However, the decisions may give an impulse to the updating
process, he added.
</P>
<P>
On the prevailing situation in Bosnia, Primakov said both
Russia and the U.S. have agreed to consistently promote the
implementation of the Dayton agreements.
</P>
<P>
"To ensure this, joint projects on the economic unification of
the Serb Republic and the Muslim-Croat Federation into one state
must be discussed," he added.
</P>
<P>
On the Middle East peace process, Primakov said that Russia and
the U.S. would take advantage of their influences in the world to
make joint efforts to have the peace process kept moving forward.
</P>
<P>
Both Russia and the U.S. planned to play a more active role in
mediation among the rivals in Middle East, he added.
</P>
<P>
However, Primakov admitted that Russia and the U.S. had different
views on the entry of the Baltic countries into the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
Russia opposes the entry of the Baltic countries into NATO, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
But it is necessary to set up a security system for the Baltic
countries, he said, adding that the system can be sponsored by
Russia or jointly sponsored by Russia and the Baltic countries.
</P>
<P>
At the invitation of Primakov, Albright arrived in
St. Petersburg on Saturday on a two-day visit to Russia before her
visit to Lithuania, one of the Baltic countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
