<HEADLINE> Egypt Commissions Two U.S.-Made Frigates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
today observed a ceremony of flag-hoisting atop two U.S.-made
Perry class frigates that joined the Egyptian navy recently, the
Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The two guided missile frigates, named Mubarak and Taba, after
the president and a Sinai resort town, are formally enlisted into
commission in the grand ceremony in the Mediterranean port city of
Alexandria this morning.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. is also providing Egypt with 10 anti-submarine
helicopters which can be based on board the frigates as well as
the destroyers serving with the Egyptian navy, according to the Al
Ahram weekly.
</P>
<P>
With the helicopters on board, the frigates will be able to
operate as mobile defense units protecting other vessels against
air and sea attacks. One of them will take part in a joint naval
exercise with Saudi Arabia next month.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is expected to recruit two other U.S. frigates into its
navy in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the ceremony, Commander of the Naval Forces
Vice-Admiral Ahmed Saber Selim said that the Egyptian naval forces
were able to assimilate the advanced technology of the weapons it
purchased from abroad.
</P>
<P>
The naval units which joined the Egyptian fleet recently group
the two U.S.-made frigates and several mine sweepers, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak, accompanied by Prime Minister Kamal el-Ganzouri,
inspected both ships at the Ras el-Tin naval base in Alexandria.
</P>
</TEXT>
