<HEADLINE> Woman Killed as 12 Cars Collide in Southern Tehran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 13 (Xinhua) -- A woman was killed in a massive
collision of 12 cars due to low visibility caused by smoke from
burning reeds near a road south of Tehran yesterday, an evening
paper reported here today.
</P>
<P>
The Persian newspaper Kayhan reported that Safiyeh Cheraghi
died after being transferred to a hospital whereas an unspecified
number of other people suffered injuries.
</P>
<P>
The accident gave rise to a traffic jam along the road. The
police and firemen called to the scene were able to end the jam
after five hours, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It said the road connecting Shahr-e Ray, located in the
southern part of Tehran, to Varamin, some 40 kilometers further
south has be notorious for traffic problems which endangered
passengers' lives.
</P>
<P>
"The road is narrow, and dark at night; it lacks required
traffic signs," the report said.
</P>
<P>
Iran has reportedly one of the highest traffic accident rates
in the world - with 205,000 collisions registered last Iranian
calendar year (March 1995 - March 96) for some 3 million cars.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian capital of Tehran actually saw the most chaotic
traffic in the world, the report added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
