<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Government Asks To Implement Open-ended Grain Purchase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Vice-premier Zhu Rongji, speaking
to a two-day meeting on grain purchase and sales today, urged
government offices nationwide to be strict in implementing the
state grain purchase policy that says local governments should buy
grain at protective prices from growers in an "open-ended" way.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was attended by heads of ministries and senior
agricultural officials from all provinces, municipalities and
autonomous regions.
</P>
<P>
Zhu, who is also a member of the Standing Committee of the
Political Bureau of the Central Committee of the Communist Party
of China, said, "The policy is an important decision of the
Central Committee of the Communist Party of China and the State
Council for favorable agricultural development and the sustained,
speedy and sound development of the overall national economy."
</P>
<P>
The policy says that the state grain system must purchase grain
at subsidized prices and that state buyers can not reject, stop,
or limit grain purchase, or pay farmers with IOUs.
</P>
<P>
It also says that financial institutions should ensure
sufficient funds for this, and prohibits the use of this capital
for other purposes.
</P>
<P>
Vice-premier Li Lanqing, a member of Political Bureau of the
CPC Central Committee, spoke at the opening session of the
meeting, which was presided over by Luo Gan, state councillor and
secretary-general of the State Council.
</P>
<P>
China is expected to harvest 118 billion kg of grain this
summer, a 3.5 percent increase, or four billion kg, more than in
1996, an all-time high, according to the Ministry of
Agriculture. This will also be the third consecutive year that
China has had a good summer harvest.  
</P>
</TEXT>
