<DOCNO> XIE19970713.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Early Childhood Education Program Underway in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government is
undertaking a Early Childhood Education and Development Program
in a bid to assist about 1.5 million children in poor households
in the country.
</P>
<P>
Under the five-year program, the existing 20,000 pre-school
day-centers will be improved and 5,000 new ones set up in 14
districts where early education and development classes are in
the open or under trees, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
During the program period from 1997 to 2002, 13,000 teachers
will be trained while 8,000 more will receive refresher courses
in nutrition, health care, child-care and management of day-care
centers.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's Permanent Secretary of the Education Ministry
Elizabeth Masiga said, "Our objective is to curb inadequate physical
and mental development of children in the pre-school years."
</P>
<P>
By increasing access to child-care for poor households, she
noted, the program will have far reaching impact on opportunities
for schooling for girls.
</P>
<P>
In Kenya, about 3 million children under the age of six come
from families living below the poverty line and 50 percent of
them suffer from malnutrition.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank has agreed to provide 27.8 million U.S. Dollars
for the program while the Kenyan government is contributing 4.6
million Dollars to it.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank has asked the government to increase its
budgetary allocation to early childhood education and
development programs.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the government allocates about half a Dollar per
child for early childhood education, said the bank, adding
that this amount is too low compared to the funding in the other
sectors of education.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan government allocates 37 Dollars for a primary
school pupil, 100 Dollars for a secondary school student and
1,300 Dollars for a university student.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that this was a unique program in sub-Saharan
Africa. World Bank education experts are optimistic about the
success of the program since Kenya acts as the home for the
Africa Early Childhood and Development Network. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
