<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2,000 Year-Old Wooden, Bamboo Strips Unearthed in Hunan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- More than 100 bamboo and wooden
strips dating back nearly 2,000 years have been unearthed in a
downtown area of this capital of central China's Hunan Province.
</P>
<P>
Chinese archeologists say that it is the first time that such
strips dating from the Eastern Han Dynasty (25-220) have ever been
found.
</P>
<P>
They are detailed records of the political, economic, cultural
and social conditions of the time. They also give insights into
the development of ancient Chinese calligraphy and literature.
</P>
<P>
The strips, which are three cm to five cm wide and about 23 cm
long, fall into the categories of government documents, official
name lists, and calligraphic works.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the archeologists have discovered 36 sites dating
from the Warring States Period (475-221 B.C.) to the Qing Dynasty
(1644-1911). Some 1,000 items of historical relics have been
unearthed, including tiles, bricks, pottery, and wooden and iron
objects for daily use.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
