<DOCNO> XIE19970713.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heart Disease Becomes Epidemic In S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Heart disease has become an
epidemic killer in South Africa and needs urgent attention, local
daily "Sunday Tribune" quoted a medical expert as reporting
today.
</P>
<P>
Sister Bernie Mothilall, an medical expert at a cardiac
hospital in Durban, said that of about 400 people tested for
cholesterol readings at a workshop in March, 38 percent fell
within the high risk range, 13 percent into extremely high risk
range and 42 percent had high blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
According to another study, 75,000 Indians in Durban, the
capital of Kwazulu Natal Province, were estimated to be in need
of heart rehabilitation while only 100 people of all races were
seeking treatment. There are about one million Indians in South
Africa.
</P>
<P>
Fifty percent of the people tested had at least one major risk
factor including a family history of cardiovascular disease,
smoking, diabetes, high cholesterol or hypertension, the study
said.
</P>
<P>
A cardiologist said that South African Indians had one of the
highest incidence of heart disease in the world. "The situation
is really reaching epidemic proportions in the country, together
with the increasing emergence of heart disease particularly in
the black community," he added.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the increase in the incidence of heart disease
to a change in lifestyle, resulting in an increase in smoking,
stress and eating habits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
