<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Residents Preserving Cultural Relics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Citizens of the Chinese capital of
Beijing, a city endowed with a history of more than three
millennia and over 7,000 cultural relics and historical sites, are
doing more to preserve their national treasures.
</P>
<P>
Many people are donating their collections of cultural relics
to appropriate departments. More than 30,000 bricks of the ancient
city wall have been donated since the municipal government
initiated the plan to renovate a section of the wall, which is the
only remaining part of that built during the Ming Dynasty
(1368-1644).
</P>
<P>
Since the 1950s, the Palace Museum in Beijing has received a
gift of more than 20,000 cultural relics, including paintings,
jade, and seals from people of all walks of life.
</P>
<P>
More national treasures have been located and saved because of
the spreading awareness of cultural relics.
</P>
<P>
Relics of prehistoric mankind and fossils of ancient plants and
animals have been discovered and turned over to cultural relics
authorities by construction workers at building sites this year.
</P>
<P>
Some villages famous for historical sites have set up their own
preservation organizations, and villagers raised money among
themselves to maintain the areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
