<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Manufacturers Call for Major Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Manufacturers in Nigeria, facing
the pains of the harsh operating environment, have called on
the government to take steps for major reforms.
</P>
<P>
The manufacturers identified the factors that they considered
as monumental impediments to the nation's economic growth as
continued lack of commitment to the privatization of government
parastatals, the Guardian reported today.
</P>
<P>
The factors also include the government's disinterest in the
affairs of small and medium scale enterprises, inadequate
attention to energy matters and non-establishment of specialized
industrial courts for quick dispensation of justice on matters
between industry and other parties.
</P>
<P>
According to an official of the Manufacturers Association of
Nigeria (MAN), the hopes held out by the 1997 budget for
accelerted agricultural and industrial activities have not
materialized half-way into the year.
</P>
<P>
The impact of the budget was yet to be felt because of the
non-release of the capital vote for the first quarter or even
half way into the year.
</P>
<P>
The bane of manufacturers in the country, according to him,
can be listed as recession, illiquidity, consumer resistance,
gross capacity under-utilization, infrastructural insufficiency,
insecurity of life and property, product adulteration and blatant
infringement of registered trade marks.
</P>
<P>
Thus the MAN urged the government to propel the economy
forward by beginning a reflation of the economy through prudent
spendings on capital projects with good linkage effects.
</P>
<P>
"The government must pay some verifiable domestic debts to
local contractors and suppliers, and upgrade the purchasing power
of the individual through a reveiw of incomes, salaries and
wages," said Gbenga Akinnawo, a MAN branch chairman.
</P>
<P>
These would increase demand for factory products, thereby
increasing the much-needed capacity utilization, he said.
</P>
<P>
The MAN also called on the government to tackle the issues of
deteriorating and inadequate infrastructure facilities,
privatization of key parastatals, promotion of small and medium
scale enterprises, and energy production and supply.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
