<HEADLINE> British Police Attacked in Northern Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 13 (Xinhua) -- British policemen in Londonderry
and north Belfast, capital of Northern Ireland, were attacked with
petrol bombs on Saturday night after the main day of the Orange
Order's marching calendar passed without any major incidents.
</P>
<P>
Gangs using catapults armed with ball-bearings were also
involved in the attacks and Royal Ulster Constabulary (RUC)
officers responded by firing plastic bullets and making some
arrests, according to BBC television reports.
</P>
<P>
Several RUC officers were slightly hurt in the over-night
violent attacks, the reports said. Elsewhere, a Protestant Orange
Order hall in County Down was also attacked by a gang with petrol
bombs.
</P>
<P>
The Protestants in Northern Ireland had planned to stage a
series of marches in Belfast, Londonderry and other cities on July
12 to celebrate the 307 anniversary of a Protestant victory over
the Catholic monarch.
</P>
<P>
The major parades were later cancelled or rerouted in an effort
to avoid large-scale violence between Protestants and Catholic
residents in the region. 
</P>
