<HEADLINE> Newsmen Face Trial for Libeling Egyptian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Egypt's Prosecution Office Saturday
ordered the trial of three Egyptian journalists and three Saudis
on charges of libeling President Hosni Mubarak's two sons, the
Egyptian Gazette reported today.
</P>
<P>
The six men are accused of printing a slanderous story about
the business dealings of Ala and Gamal.
</P>
<P>
Last month, Mubarak's sons filed a report to the prosecutor's
office complaining about the corruption allegations against them
that appeared in the Saudi-owned Asharq Al-Awsat newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The allegations appeared in an advertisement printed on the
newspaper's sister magazine Al-Jadida, but publishers withdrew the
article before distribution.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian journalist Sayed Abdel-Atti, author of the article,
and Fawzieh Salama and Gamal Ismail, Al-Jadida editors who have
since been dismissed from the London-based magazine, have been
ordered to appear in court.
</P>
<P>
Saudis Hesham and Mohammed Ali Hafez, publishers of the
Al-Jadida and Sharq Al-Awsat, as well as Othman al-Omaer, the
paper's editor-in-chief, will also face trial.
</P>
<P>
If found guilty, the accused will face a maximum penalty of
three years in jail and a fine of 750,000 Egyptian pounds (221,000
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The date of trial has yet to be set. And some of the accused
would be tried in default, some court sources were quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak's sons accused the article of containing "lies and
various baseless allegations about transactions, commissions and
illusionary monopolies with a premeditated aim of inflicting
severe harm and slander" on the family. 
</P>
</TEXT>
