<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Plants Ordered to Close Down for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 13 (Xinhua) --Three Tanzanian factories
have been ordered to close down for polluting the environment
with industrial effluents, said a report available here today.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanian Vice-President Omar Ali Juma made the order
Saturday when he toured the three factories in Dar es Salaam
following complaints from residents that the industrial effluents
emitted by the three factories posed a great danger to their
lives.
</P>
<P>
Factories involved are the Trans-Tech which manufactures
cooking oil, Tanpack which makes tissue paper, and Mortans
Limited, a producer of zinc oxide, rubber products and automobile
spare parts.
</P>
<P>
The three factories can resume production after installation
of facilities for the disposal of industrial wastes.
</P>
<P>
Omar urged the three firms to adopt cleaner production
technologies and to collectively construct a central sewerage
system.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the need for all factories in the country to
install recycling plants, saying the facilities are vital in
checking pollution of the environment by toxic wastes or
materials that could not be broken down biologically such as
plastics and other synthetics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
