<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Books On Complete History of Anti-Japanese War Published </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, July 13 (Xinhua) -- A series of books covering the
complete history of China's war of resistance to Japanese invasion
have been published on the occasion of the 60th anniversary of the
July 7 Incident, the opening salvo in the war.
</P>
<P>
The series, starting from Japan's invasion of northeast China
in 1931 to its surrender in 1945, is titled "The War of
Resistance Against Japanese Aggression". It contains photographs,
documents, archives, memoirs and diaries concerning politics,
economy, culture, military affairs, diplomacy and outrages
committed by the Japanese invaders during that period.
</P>
<P>
Some of the documents and archives in the books, including
those published in Taiwan or after the founding of People's
Republic of China in 1949, as well as diplomatic documents of the
United States, Britain, Japan, the Soviet Union, Germany and
France, are for the first time made public in China.
</P>
<P>
The eleven-volume series was compiled by the Chinese Historical
Studies Society and the Institute of Modern Chinese History under
the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences. It was published by the
Sichuan University Publishing House.
</P>
<P>
Japanese troops provoked the September 18 Incident in 1931 to
start a full-scale invasion of northeast China. The July 7
Incident of 1937 in west Beijing signaled the start of the
eight-year national anti-Japanese war. The Japanese surrendered on
August 15, 1945. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
