<HEADLINE> Jarrett Beats Jackson in World Track Trials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Tony Jarrett beat world record
holder Colin Jackson for the first time in the men's 110-meter
hurdles at the Britain world championships trials in Birmingham on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Jarrett trailed home in 13.33 seconds, ahead of his old rival
Jackson who crossed the line in 13.39 seconds. This is Jarrett's
first victory over Jackson. Jarrett currently ranked only 20th in
the world. He was beaten by the world record holder three times
this season.
</P>
<P>
Both have places in Britain's team for the world championships
in Athens next month.
</P>
<P>
Ian Mackie was also pleased with his performance. He won the
100 meters title without Linford Christie's appearence, clocking
10.28 seconds.
</P>
<P>
The 41-year-old Tessa Sanderson is going to Athens 23 years
after her first appearing in a major competition -- the 1974
Ruropean Championshops. She won the javelin with a throw of 58.30
metres.
</P>
<P>
Kelly Holmes won the 800 meters in one minute 58.69 seconds.
She earlier said she would also competed in 1500 meters.
</P>
<P>
Sally Gunnell, the former Olympic and world 400 meters hurdles
champion, won Sunday's 400 hurdles final in 55.71 seconds. 
