<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South China Sea Oilfields Increase Crude Oil Output </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The oilfields in the South China
Sea yielded 6.78 million tons of crude oil during the first half
of this year, a 31 percent rise over the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The oilfields, which are being exploited through Sino-foreign
cooperation, are expected to lift their crude oil output to 12
million tons this year from 11.84 million tons in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The oilfields come under the jurisdiction of the Eastern South
China Sea Company, which is one of the regional companies of the
China National Offshore Oil Corporation (CNOOC).
</P>
<P>
Nine oilfields have proved to be commercially worthy of
exploitation in the South China Sea; eight of them have already
gone into operation.
</P>
<P>
The Eastern South China Sea Company has forged cooperative
relations with 38 foreign counterparts from 11 countries and
regions, including the US, Britain and Italy. It has signed 43
contracts with foreign companies for the recovery of oil.  
</P>
</TEXT>
