<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Commercial Banks Fund Big Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 13 (Xinhua) -- China's large industrial
corporations, the backbone of the country's economy, are expected
to gain more support from the commercial banks when applying for
loans, according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
"Supporting large state enterprises is not only our duty, but
also a key strategy for our expansion," Yang Kaisheng,
vice-president of the Industrial and Commercial Bank of China
(ICBC), was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
ICBC is acting as the sponsoring bank for 90 percent of the 512
pilot conglomerates.
</P>
<P>
The sponsoring bank practice was adopted last year across the
country. Under a fixed cooperation relationship, a sponsoring bank
offers its partner enterprise credit and consulting services,
while the enterprise opens accounts and does financial
transactions in the bank.
</P>
<P>
The large state firms this year would receive 80 percent of the
bank's 40 billion yuan loans. The supported firms include
Changhong Television, Yizheng Chemical Fiber, Daqing Oil and First
Auto Works, all stars in their trade.
</P>
<P>
China Construction Bank (CCB), which initiated the strategy of
supporting large corporations two years ago, also benefits from
the move.
</P>
<P>
"By focusing on large conglomerates and giving up poorly
performed small firms, our bank achieved good returns last year,"
said Liu Rengang, deputy general manager of the bank's credit
management department.
</P>
<P>
According to Liu, about 95 percent of the loans can be
collected back on time, and problem loans account for no more than
one percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
Taking advantage of the bank's forces in investment banking, the
bank also offers unique services in the capital market for its
clientele.
</P>
<P>
"To develop large corporations and large industrial groups will
resolve the poor returns from a scattered extensive input," Liu
noted.
</P>
<P>
CCB has simplified loan procedures for conglomerates.
</P>
<P>
The official said that 70 percent of its working capital loans
go to such sectors as energy, petroleum, post and telecoms,
transportation and chemical.
</P>
<P>
To ensure the safety of loans, the commercial banks have worked
out methods to tighten auditing and supervision. CCB, for
instance, has set up a risk-monitoring system for credit check
before, during and after loans are granted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
