<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Savings Decline Arouses Concern of Banks' Liability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The slowdown of new savings
deposits this year is a warning that Chinese banks must improve
their liability management, said a Chinese financial analyst on a
recent interview with China Daily.
</P>
<P>
According to today's China Daily, Lin Zhiyuan, professor of the
Research Institute of Finance and Banking under the People's Bank
of China, said that the drop of savings is a natural result
of cash flowing into the booming securities market after interest
rate cuts last year.
</P>
<P>
During the January-May period, new individuals savings accounts
amounted to about 350 billion yuan (US$42 billion), down about 140
billion yuan from the same period last year, according to the
State Information Center.
</P>
<P>
Many Chinese people lost interest in savings accounts after
China twice cut interest rates last year and transferred their money
to the securities markets to seek higher returns.
</P>
<P>
Through the securities market, the money goes to enterprises,
which ultimately deposit the money in banks, Lin said.
</P>
<P>
Under this situation, the liability structure of Chinese banks
is changing. Enterprises are making more non-fixed deposits, and
fewer individuals are making fixed-term deposits. As a result,
the banks' debts become more fluid.
</P>
<P>
"The increased fluidity will add risks to banking operations
and cause the banks to become more sensitive to economic
fluctuation, " Lin said.
</P>
<P>
She noted that domestic banks must improve the management to
respond quickly to liability changes. Considering the banks'
endurance of sluggish savings deposits, the country's
interest rates on savings accounts should remain unchanged this
year to maintain the stability of the banking system. However she
added that the central bank's interest rate should be cut as early
as possible, saying that China's interests rates are still higher than in
foreign countries, which means domestic banks are unable to
compete in investment markets. enditem
nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
