<HEADLINE> Army Called Out to Help Flood Victims in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The flash flood that hit nearly
one-third of Bangladesh has deteriorated further and the
government called out the armed forces to undertake emergency
rescue and relief operations in the affected areas.
</P>
<P>
The death toll in the sudden flood, caused by incessant
downpours for the last five days and on-rush of hilly water, has
risen to 57 as reports of fresh deaths are still reaching Dhaka
from the flood-hit areas.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina, before leaving for Germany on
Saturday, ordered the deployment of the army for emergency rescue
and relief operations in the flood-affected areas. Air Force
helicopters have already been used to drop relief supplies to the
marooned people.
</P>
<P>
The incessant rainfall and on-rush of hilly water from across
the border inundated vast areas in the country's northern and
southeastern regions and disrupted road and rail communication in
some districts.
</P>
<P>
The capital city of Dhaka remains cut off from the northern
districts as the Aricha-Nagarbari ferry service was suspended on
Saturday noon while the road between Chittagong and the Cox's
Bazar has been closed for the fourth consecutive day today.
</P>
<P>
In Dhaka, heavy rainfall caused flooding in all low-lying areas
around it while the vegetables markets, most of them waterlogged,
were running out of supplies, causing a temporary hike of fish,
meat and vegetables prices.
</P>
<P>
According to the Flood Information Center, at least 11 rivers
of the three major river basins have been flowing above their
respective danger marks with the rise in water levels on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Brahmaputra and the Ganges continued to rise at all points
while the rivers in the Meghna basin recorded both rises and falls
and all the rivers in the southeastern hill basin continued to
rise at all points, the center added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
