<HEADLINE> Nepal Government Criticized for Newsprint Duty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The Nepali government has come
under a barrage of criticism after it proposed to impose a
5-percent duty on imported newsprint.
</P>
<P>
Members of parliament from different political parties voiced
in unison opposition to the proposal, demanding instead that the
government withdraw the proposal and provide more assistance to
the fledgling newsprint industry, the national press reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Former Communications Minister Chiranjibi Wagle also lashed the
government's move, saying the newsprint produced in Nepal
constitutes just a small portion of total market demand as the
newspaper industry is basically dependent on foreign newsprint.
</P>
<P>
The government's duty proposal also met strong condemnation
from the print industry.
</P>
<P>
President of the Nepalese Journalists Federation Harihar Birahi
said his organization has been demanding more subsidy on the
newsprint. If the government imposes duty in such a condition, the
price for newsprint is sure to go up, which in turn will have an
adverse impact on print journalism.
</P>
<P>
President of Nepal Editors' Society Govind Biyogi said there is
no point for the government to impose such burdens on the print
media.
</P>
<P>
Nepal has some 160 regular publications, including 21 dailies
and 129 weeklies.  
</P>
</TEXT>
