<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guatemalan President Highlights Regional Integration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Guatemalan President Alvaro
Arzu said today that Central America restarted the regional
integration after ending the armed conflicts that bled some of the
nations.
</P>
<P>
"We are in Panama to carry forward all our region toward new
horizons of joint development," said Arzu in a speech during the
one-day summit of the Central America opened here today.
</P>
<P>
Guatemala assumed today the semi-annual presidency of the
council of foreign, economy and foreign trade ministers of Central
America.
</P>
<P>
The Guatemalan president said that since the third decade of
the 19th century, when the federation that followed the
emancipation from Spain was broken, 21 of the 22 countries in the
region failed to integrate.
</P>
<P>
Central America has had serious political, economic and social
problems in the past years, and there were internecine armed
confrontations in Guatemala, El Salvador and Nicaragua, said the
Guatemalan president.
</P>
<P>
He underlined the importance of regional collaboration in the
face of economic globalization, not only intergovernmental, but
also the transformation in depth of the institutional scaffolding
of integration.
</P>
<P>
He advocated "a solid, consistent and correct" institutional
change to strengthen, intensify and develop regional collaboration.
</P>
<P>
The Central American presidential summit expects to adopt some
fundamental decisions on the reforms of the Central American
Parliament and Court. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
