<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Tamil Rebels Release DPRK Crew Members </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 12 (xinhua) -- Thirty-seven crew members of a
Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) ship abducted by the
Sri Lankan Tamil rebels were released today, a spokesman of the
International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC) said here.
</P>
<P>
He said the crew members were handed over to the committee by
the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) at Mallawi in the
Wanini District of northern Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the crew members, expected to arrive here
tonight, would be handed over to the shipping company's
representatives at the ICRC headquarters here.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE rebels abducted the ship and its 38 crew members on
Tuesday and killed one of them, whose body was handed over to the
ICRC on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The vessel, hired by Sri Lanka to transport goods to the Jaffna
Peninsula, was on its way to Colombo Tuesday when it was abducted
at Millaitivu, more than 200 kilometers north of the destination.
</P>
</TEXT>
