<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil to Export 7 Million Tons of Sugar This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Brazil will increase its
sugar export to 7 million tons this year after its eliminating
sugar export quotas, a Brazilian official has said.
</P>
<P>
Julio Maria Borges, consultant to the Central Bank of Brazil,
said the bank announced Friday the elimination of quotas to sugar
exports.
</P>
<P>
By eliminating the quota, Brazil can export up to 7 million
tons of sugar this year, a volume higher than the 5.2 million tons
permitted by the government.
</P>
<P>
The present export surplus does not justify the 40 percent tax
created to guarantee the domestic supply.
</P>
<P>
Present sugar prices, 12.50-13 U.S. dollars for a 50-kilogram
bag, are being pressured down by the big surplus of
sugar, said Borges.
</P>
<P>
Brazil is the biggest producer and exporter of sugar in the
world. Last year it produced 12 million tons of sugar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
