<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 8th Pan-Arab Games Opens in Beirut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The eighth Pan-Arab Games opened in
Beirut tonight with more than 2,000 athletes from 19 countries
registered to compete in 20 events.
</P>
<P>
The Games opened in a magnificent ceremony held in the Beirut
Sports City Stadium, which had been destroyed in the 1982
bombardment of West Beirut by Israel, and was reconstructed during
the past two years with 100 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Athletes, guided by national flags of their countries, walked
into the noisy stadium in rows, warmly welcomed by an audience of
more than 50,000.
</P>
<P>
Juan Antonio Samaranch, President of the International Olympic
Committee, Esmat Abdul-Maguid, secretary general of the Arab
League, and other Lebanese political leaders and foreign diplomats
took part in the opening ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon successfully held the second Pan-Arab Games in 1957.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, 95 Iraqi athletes returned home this
afternoon after the Lebanese authorities refused their entry in
fear of infruiating Kuwait and Saudi Arabia, the two funders of
the Beirut Sports City's rebuilding and main financers for
Lebanon's ambitious reconstruction schemes.
</P>
<P>
Carried by four buses, the Iraqi team arrived at the Masnaa
Cross on the Lebanese-Syrian border Friday morning and threatened
to stage a protest if they were not allowed to take part in the
Games in Beirut.
</P>
<P>
In 1992, after failing to obtain Syria's permission to
attend the Seventh Pan-Arab Games, the Iraqi delegation returned
to Amman and staged a sit-on on the Syrian-Lebanese border.
</P>
<P>
Due to a strict international sanction against their country,
the 160 Libyan athletes had to take a roundabout route to Lebanon
via Tunis and Italy. The Libyans will tark part in 12 events.
</P>
<P>
The competition will start on Sunday and go on until 27 with
the participation of 1,645 men and 470 women from Algeria,
Bahrain, Djibouti, Egypt, Jordan, Kuwait, Lebanon, Libya,
Mauritania, Morocco, Oman, Palestine, Qatar, Saudi arabia, Sudan,
Syria, the United Arab Emirates, Tunis and Yemen.
</P>
<P>
Among the events will be track and field, soccer, basketball,
swimming, tennis, shooting, wrestling, golf and gymnastics.
</P>
</TEXT>
