<HEADLINE> Higher Gold Output Expected in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 13 (Xinhua) -- China's gold output in the
January-June period this year reached 60 tons, representing an 18
percent increase from the same period of 1996, according to
today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that China's gold industry officials are now
optimistic about meeting the goals this year because the country
has met 60 percent of the target set by the State Planning
Commission for the first half of the year.
</P>
<P>
The officials said that the January-June output also approaches
half the production goal set by the gold bureau. The gold mines
usually produce more gold in the second half of a year than in the
first half for seasonal reasons.
</P>
<P>
Shandong Province ranks first in output, with 538,000 taels,
the equivalent of 16,812 kg.
</P>
<P>
Henan follows with 227,000 taels; Hebei, with 144,000 taels;
and Shaanxi, 144,000 taels.
</P>
<P>
Other gold producers are Xinjiang, Gansu, Hunan, Guangxi,
Anhui, Sichuan, Yunnan, Beijing, Fujian and Guangdong.
</P>
<P>
Unlike other industries closely integrated with the
international market, China's gold industry is still under state
planning. Gold produced by the mines is purchased by the People's
Bank of China.
</P>
<P>
China produced more than 120 tons of gold last year, ranking
sixth in the world. A senior Gold Bureau official said that the
gold output this year is expected to hit 130 tons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
