<HEADLINE> New NATO Entrants to Enhance Military Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Defense ministers of Hungary,
Poland and the Czech Republic, the three states invited earlier
this week to join NATO, agreed to strengthen their military
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"We have come to an agreement that we shall have closer
cooperation in terms of the development of armed forces," the
three ministers said in a joint statement today.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed that they would hold regular meeting every
three months during the up-coming process of NATO accession talks.
</P>
<P>
To enter NATO was the common interest of the three countries,
the ministers added.
</P>
<P>
As for relations with other eastern European countries that
also applied for NATO memberships, the ministers said that their
countries would like to expand cooperation with them.
</P>
<P>
Polish Defense Minister Stanislaw Dobrzanski and Czech Defense
Minister Miloslav Vyborny are here for a one-day working visit
invited by their Hungarian counterpart, Keleti Gyorgy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
